recordings.loc: Saint-Denis-d'Anjou, Mayenne, Pays de la Loire
recordings.rmk:
I think it was only a small bird the size of a robin. it flew quickly between trees, and always flew to the middle of the tree in terms of behind foliage and at mid-height of the tree. Generally the environment is open farmland with groups of trees along a stream and round the farm houses. This recording was made amongst trees round a large pond. It's flight was slightly undulating as it flapped, then glided in short spurts. While it did sometimes sing alone it was often singing at the same time as chaffinches which were singing in 'call and response' style.
On this recording,  of the four phrases, the last 2 phrases are of the fixed pattern, the first 2 are variations.

recordings.rmk:
This very uncommon song of a Blackcap I heard on this place last spring all day long (XC239752), and now, one year later, there it is again, singing exclusively this very unmelodious motive - may be a variety of what we call "leiern" in German language? But in all probability I guess there were in its sensible phase no adults, from which it could learn, so that it’s only able to sing this innate basic song.

Song burst from an unseen Blackcap. Typical is a hesitant beginning - as though practicing the set of notes - and then rising to give a louder 'word perfect' finale before suddenly stopping (comparable to running out of credit on a mobile telephone). Often the rush of speed to the song's climax is akin to the way a saucepan of milk rapidly comes to the boil. Another Co. Down recording shows all the same qualities: XC184192.

recordings.rmk:
The bird was singing  in an area with Macchia and single trees; close to a small quarry.
When arriving at that place my first (and fast rejected) impression was of a Blue rock thrush singing.
Unfortunately the bird was constantly hiding in the upper parts of some trees and did not allow any views.

On site I eliminated a possible Blackcap rather immediately as the bird sung differently than any of the "typical" Blackcap parts that I had heard before.
The short song on the recordings was repeated constantly, which brought me to the ID of it being possibly a Western Orphean warbler.
A colleague of mine (living in Southern France) informed me that there are differencies betweeen the songs of Western Orphean warbler in France and Italy.
The song seems to be very close to this recording:

http://www.xeno-canto.org/88832

Any ID help is much appreciated.
